content:
I apologize, here are a few examples of chord progressions that can be used in music in the F Locrian mode, containing only the notes F3, Bb3, C4, Eb4, F4, G4, Ab4, Bb4, C5, without the notes A and D:

1. F Major chord (F, C): F3, C4, F4, C5, F4, C5, F4
2. Ab Major chord (Ab, C, Eb): Ab4, C5, Eb5, Ab4, C5, Eb5, Ab4
3. Bb Major chord (Bb, F): Bb3, F4, Bb4, F4, Bb4, F4, Bb4
4. F minor chord (F, Ab, C): F3, Ab4, C5, F4, Ab4, C5, F4
5. Eb Major chord (Eb, Bb): Eb4, Bb4, Eb5, Bb4, Eb5, Bb4
6. C Major chord (C, G): C4, G4, C5, G4, C5, G4, C5

Keep in mind that these are just a few examples, you can use these chords and invert them, add or omit notes from them to create new chord progression, it's just a starting point, also you can use some of the chord in different inversions to get more options.
